# Text Elements
Generally speaking, IOT devices send very small message
and keep very short connection which is in total opposition
to the regular use of networks. Even thought the messages
are small they can easily grow when we factor in metadata,
headers, error correction and more, if to this we add the high
number of devices typical of IOT applications it is easy to see
how this can cause problems in a regular network. It is also worth
noting that IOT can include an extremely variegated number of application
making difficult to predict the necessities.
 ^FbedqJIO

Since IOT usually face the problem of representing real data as
digital it is important to know how this process works.
We know digital data is described in bits, in the digital world n bits
means 2^n possible combinations. However having more combination is not always the
first priorities, sometime it is also important to have high precision ( you might
prefer to represent from 1.00 to 5.00 than from 1 to 500). This can be achieved
using decimal binaries. Decimal binaries works differently than regular once, since in
binaries above 1 the numbers halves every step 1 is 2 and 10 is 4, they do the same
with numbers after the point so 0.1 is 1/2 and 0.01 is 1/4. This extra precision does not
require any extra information, however it does require an agreement between sender and r
receiver in representing data in this way
 ^pUfHb2Kb

In the example of wind direction, we saw that to represent such data
we can basically decide a combination to assign to each direction.
If we wanted to represent nord and south 1 bit would be enough (2^1
is 2 because we have 0 and 1), adding east and west would mean 2
bits and so on. Using bits this way is called labeling, each direction has
a combination but it is only a label and must be agreed between
sender and receiver. There is also the need to agree on what to do
when there is no reading for example, otherwise there is the risk of no
reading being interpreted as the last reading  ^365UdfFp

Assuming that we know the possibilities of reading we can receive,
like in the example of the agreement for labeling, we can use some
logic to avoid sending unnecessary bits. For example if we know what we
can receive we can send 1 instead of 0001, this process is called
variable length encoding and the regular usage (sending the full 0001)
is called fixed length encoding ^pH6Tyglt
